comment.editorialComment: September forecast has been moved to level now on the back of recent Black Book movements. It is unlikely that these values will change again before the end of the month.

What was once seen as the traditional seasonal lift in values as we approached the end of the year has all but disappeared now. The main reason for this is that this sector has grown enormously over the last few years and with almost every manufacturer offering a derivative that purports to be an SUV, this sector of the market has become very crowded. That isn’t to say that there isn’t demand from both trade and retail buyers, it is more about the fact that they have become more of an everyday car and certain models in particular are dominating the market which is starting to put pressure on values. So instead of expecting to see values rising or falling, our view is that things will remain relatively flat during October.

November is usually a fairly flat month for this sector with values just holding on until the winter takes a grip and suddenly everybody wants a 4WD. This would also be the time of the year when the canny buyers would start to build stock levels in anticipation of the sudden rush in demand and subsequently the lift in values that would follow. However, this sector has grown tremendously over the past few years and apart from the true 4X4’s, there is little else to differentiate it from some of the more normal sectors. We believe however, that there will still be a reasonable demand for product through November and that values will move back by around -0.5%.
